Germany, Year Zero
It's May 8 that always reminds me of the year 1945. Because the end of the war in Europe was truly a decisive moment in my life.
When the first Soviet soldiers arrived in our small street, in the suburbs of west Berlin, we knew that the great massacre was coming to an end.
My father, a resistance fighter, would return from the Brandenburg prison.
I would no longer have to hide myself as I did after my liberation from a Gestapo camp at the beginning of February.
It was the beginning of a new life.
But first, there was chaos.
The Nazis departed, the occupying powers had not yet set up an administration.
We're looting the stores in the neighborhood. I still have a few volumes of romantic poetry that I recovered from a bookstore.
I was sixteen years old. The occupying armies were committing every excess.
It was difficult to get food.
My father was taken directly from his prison to the centre of Berlin, and tasked with setting up - from scratch - the city's energy supply office.
For a certain period, there was neither electricity nor transportation nor organized life.
Victory or liberation?
For the Germans it was a delicate question, even if for our family it was obviously a liberation in every sense of the word.
But what for?
What's in store for the future?
"You have to help", my mother says to me.
I therefore offered my services to the local Soviet authorities and participated in the delivery of basic foodstuffs to a few distribution points in our Zehlendorf district.
Five weeks later, I was back at school.
I had a special card for being a "victim of fascism", while others wore an Iron Cross awarded for late services to the army.
Some were refugees from the East, many had seen their house destroyed by bombings, almost all were crying for the loss of loved ones.
However, this stage did not last.
It is almost unbelievable, but three years later, a monetary reform and liberal policies triggered the "German economic miracle".
In other words, or more precisely, the West German economic miracle.
The differences between occupying powers were striking.
In the Soviet zone, progress was slow and mostly accompanied by a new form of oppression.
Concentration camps such as Buchenwald continued to operate, with different guards and prisoners.
In contrast, after a brief period of non-fraternization, Western powers adopted a policy of controlled autonomy reinforcement.
One year after the end of the war, there were local administrations, and two years later, elections.
Democracy was not an empty word, and it rested on German traditions.
Certainly, not all was benevolence from the occupying powers.
It was also the start of the Cold War, and each one wanted to consolidate 'his' part of Germany.
But there are still lessons to be learned from this process.
Two lessons in particular deserve to be mentioned.
The first is of an economic order, and linked to the Marshall Plan.
It may be regrettable, but democracy is undoubtedly anchored more easily in an economic recovery context.
It requires above all initiative, from individuals willing to end a period of distress.
These initiatives can be encouraged by policies (such as those of Ludwig Erhard, father of "social market economy" in Germany), but things are easier with seed capital.
The importance of American support via the Marshall Plan.
In the same way, the European Union has helped and continues to support formerly communist countries in their efforts.
The other lesson, of a moral order, is more difficult.
The Nuremberg trials made the guilt of Nazi leaders undeniable.
However, Germany has not undertaken its long path by worrying about the past.
In fact, many have described the Adenauer years after 1949 as a period of "restoration," because too many minor Nazi personalities remained in their positions.
In a certain way, the country ignored its past to move forward towards the future.
Years later, after the establishment of a market economy and a political democracy, Germany came to terms with its past, with a great deal of success.
The Nazi past is unique in its horror, and comparisons with other battered countries therefore lend to confusion.
However, in its own way, Poland followed a similar path after 1989: first the novelty, then an attempt to come to terms with the past.
In the end, it is a better method.
In Europe, May 8, 2005, is an occasion to look at the past with sadness and anger, but also to turn towards the future, proud of the achievements of the last decades and thus filled with hope.
